Inflation, in Europe, has slipped on the diet
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 countries of the euro area was greater than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, according to the statistics office of the European Community located in Luxembourg.
The official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate by saying that lowering interest rates, with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation in order to no longer have to intervene on this issue later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record over the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has picked up due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The futures market for cereals has increased by 88 percent and the soybean price has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, in the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup warns of government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December. Thus, since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Institute of Polling) has never before seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would be more than two-thirds (71 per cent) support against a fifth (20 per cent) support for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party) due to the greater determination of opposition voters.
According to the survey, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent in the entire population.
Of the loyal voters certain to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who felt that the economic situation in the country was particularly serious has never been so high, it rises to 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic prospects of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For the next year, the majority of the population expects an aggravation and only one-tenth expects an improvement in the situation.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, said the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcs<0xC3><0xA1>ny while 38 percent support Viktor Orb<0xC3><0xA1>n.
54 percent don’t trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent don’t trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change of government.
While after the October riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, currently that rate is only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believes that the holding of new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 percent of respondents said they would certainly vote and the additional 20 percent said they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be no doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to enrolment in higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees and 84 percent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look at only the same proportions of people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters, respectively, would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
Hypermarkets located in the Budaörs commercial triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year, as opposed to the fact that this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdas<0xC3><0xA1>g (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a value increase of well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, “which had already gone up” in grocery stores last December, have not risen sharply since the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily Basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by 91 forints at a minimum.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey net, nut and poppy have risen sharply.
In the shops, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread from one kilo to 139 forints was found only.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the recorded bottle of two liters of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the recorded bottle included.
Only this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased it by about 18 and 18 percent, respectively.
Comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s cheapest basket, we see a 12 percent gap while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket is 21 percent.
Prices increased by 1,480 forints on average.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate had already been noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
As this process perplexed trade, hypermarkets were visibly unable to determine what margin they would apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of changing prices on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the turnover of a product, he or she is likely to lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily basket prices was so excessive that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the 2006 value, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not that excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was higher by 1,630 forints than last year and the prices of the cheapest also increased by 1,284 forints.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH's data: for some essential feeds, the Institute of Statistics observed a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by barely more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the brutal increase in prices also accepted by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take the long-conserving food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, important queues formed at the checkout desks of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the misuse of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected on a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital but soon after he had to return to the hospital due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to do a major operation because of the bacteria that is in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Centre for Epidemiology.
We know that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of people carry the bacterium Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a bacterium that is well resistant to antibiotics that will quickly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients, low weight or with a weakened organism.
According to J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital's chief physician, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily lives of hospitals.
Above all, the infection should not be confused with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the caregivers wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling of the sample is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favorable, in Hungarian hospitals, to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection manifests mainly in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate MRSA-carrying patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases come to light only if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts need to be made to target antibiotic therapy, in other words, microbiological examinations should be performed to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz said.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, significant gaps are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs are spread by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of an epidemic, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenditures for social security funds, which is why this infection is fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
