British Army Recruits on YouTube
British Army units communicate on the video-sharing site recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to become popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has become passionate about YouTube: special forces in Afghanistan are uploading video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London or uploaded to the Internet by the compatriots.
The political message is indispensable
Air Force soldiers have already spent 139 sequences on the net via this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence signed up as "defenseheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and it communicates videos of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defense, they also served to make known to the general public the real objectives of the presence of the army abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements passed on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, told the BBC, but it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the validity of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the fighting side.
In fact, many videos had already gone online showing areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently been packing for the upload of these videos.
The Americans make the recruitment a little different by using the shooting game America's Army downloadable for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
