The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as rest days.
Rest days are often associated with religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the new year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the newcomers can rest quietly.
In one year, we have eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the revolution of 1848, as well as October 23, which is the commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1 is the Labor Day and on November 1 and 2, we remember the members of our family and our deceased friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, at Pentecost and at Christmas.
The days of our state holidays, national or even religious rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has enacted special regulations on the replacement days of the days before or after the holidays.
The Act extends to all employers and their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service companies, institutions running without interruption and in service, by their vocation, and also to rest days.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life stops almost throughout the country because according to experiences the majority of people rather do overtime or take vacations that they have saved for these purposes so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, therefore there will be fewer changes in the level of working days compared to this year.
The schedule will be reorganized for the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25th will be a working day to have a rest day on Friday, May 2nd.
Another change is planned for 23 October: Saturday 18 October will be a working day replacing Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the day of the new year falls on a Wednesday.
Six Unnecessary Things That Can Hurt Your Colleagues
Emails we forget to send, voicemails we never receive, innocent lies that annoy us almost more: these are things that “beautify” the daily life of a workplace.
The question is whether to get used to these problems or take up the challenge and consciously avoid ambiguous situations, causing trouble to others.
Examples.
“Excuse me, I forgot to tell you you were called to the marketing department,” a colleague told you.
That you missed an appointment?
At best he is sorry and tries to fix things by calling the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to pass the message (this is the least common solution).
In most cases, the matter is settled with apologies.
Before you have any painful explanations, it is helpful to think about how you can cause unpleasant moments to your colleagues and make efforts to avoid them.
Do you borrow something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s nothing more annoying than wanting to take a folder, an office tool, or the phone and you can’t find them anywhere.
Do you remember the day before you put the stapler on the desk but it disappeared the next morning?
Do you happen to find your pen that you thought was lost on your colleague's desk?
Don't take anything from your colleagues without asking, or they're right to be mad at you for picking up their property.
Do not bring envelopes, post-it in your pocket because it can be annoying that there are no more and you need them right away.
Do you care about the privacy of your colleagues?
There are no good ways to stop the spreading of rotten things.
Who did what, with whom?
Or and why?
Do not tell everyone your information (suppositions) about the privacy of your colleagues!
If a colleague shares his intimate secrets with you, do not abuse his trust!
Bury the shared information in yourself and do not discuss it with your colleagues in their absence even if your colleagues are also aware of it.
Are you claiming to be ill for no good reason?
When you call the office and declare yourself sick under the pretext of a tearing headache because you feel sick or you feel in need of rest that day, think about the fact that your work, your urgent business, your future missions must be performed by someone else in your place.
Don’t bother your colleagues!
If you know in advance that the next day you are not going to work or that something can happen that would force you to stay at home, remember to warn your boss and colleagues to prevent them from being surprised by your absence the next day.
Chilling, squeezing, telephone
You get into your job, but your co-workers snatch you out of it?
You became, unintentionally, a witness to a phone conversation that you'd be better off not listening to?
Don’t disturb your colleagues with squealing, cantoning, loud conversations (which you carry over their heads), footsteps, big words, or dissatisfaction expressed out loud.
They can disturb even if your colleagues are not immersed in a project (writing, design, organization).
Are you blaming others for a fault?
If your work is not done for the set deadline, you forget to send an important mail or message, do not blame anyone for this forgetting!
Don't put it on account of the possible chaos in the office or your noisy colleagues!
Recognize it if you have made a mistake and if it has presented inconveniences for others, fix the mistake!
Ask how you could fix your fault, fix the negligence!
Do you feel too much at home in the office?
Putting on a jogging and slippers is comfortable at home but they are not suitable for the office!
Don’t put on comfortable jogging even if your function allows it!
Do not be neglected, respect your colleagues and yourself by dressing properly, and if your job requires it by putting on nice and elegant clothes, to go to work!
