The Federal Reserve Bank of the United States, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be put into the money markets through auctions.
It will be for banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
As an example, the US Fed will auction off $40 billion and, in addition, it will provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the central banks of individual states have decided to take such concerted action to prevent or even reduce the effects of the financial crisis.
“This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend,” writes Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
“The concerted action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unrepaid loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect further losses in billions.
“If the central banks have chosen this approach, it is that they must really understand what is still to come,” said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks fear that, if banks themselves will have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect economic growth around the world.
The central banks made this choice after they failed to bring down the interbank rate of London, called LIBOR, used to borrow in the interbank market.
This meant that the banks were still afraid of mutual loans, even though the US, Canadian and English central banks repeatedly lowered their interest rates in the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further interest rate cut," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the approach of the central banks will not help to conjure up the crisis, since it does not solve the main problem that is the collapse of the US real estate market.
