A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in open access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only consultable for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and nominally, at the request of a former victim or her rightholders.
The 11 states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them up to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed and the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will allow research “in particular on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced labour,” said Reto Meistern, director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, objected to the public disclosure of these name documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported or forced labour civilians and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
