The buses bring people back to work, and to fight al Qaeda.
The first bus filled with Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, dumping those exiles without money or visa renewals, or others who hope the city has regained normalcy.
Some have returned to fight the militants who have driven them away from home.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival in Damascus of 800 people transported in the convoys of dozens of official government buses, the terminal was filled with refugees from Syria and Jordan who returned by their means.
“I decided to go to Syria after they killed several doctors in Baghdad,” said Sabah al-Kubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came home today because I saw on TV and read in the newspapers what happened in Baghdad and saw that the city is safer now.”
“They say the Mahdi army no longer commits crimes!” he said, referring to the Shia militia of ecclesiastical militant Moqtada al-Sadr, who has forced his men to move away for the time being.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shia teacher from the Sunni-dominated Amariyah area, has returned with his two children because he could no longer renew his Syrian visa and because the regime is preventing Iraqis from working.
His neighbors from Shia to Amariyah called him to inform him that the U.S.-aided militia had allowed Al Qaeda to drive out of the western capital, and invited him to return.
One of Jordan’s newcomers is the leader of a Sunni and Shia tribe who had to leave his home north of Baghdad because of a grenade attack after he incited citizens to rebel against Al Qaeda.
But he had to come home to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had set up an anti-Al Qaeda militia in Sleikh, and that they needed me and my boys.”
“That’s why I’m coming home today,” said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many say they have been drawn to the capital’s growing calm since U.S. troops arrived, and to the prospect of continuing formation of well-armed “involved citizen groups” collaborating with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhood.
But still others say they have been forced to return because of the visa problem and the decadence of the capital of Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, 51, father of three, expressed the suspicion felt by all about the visas for exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, Shia Prime Minister, who allegedly asked the Syrian government to limit to force people to return to the country.
More than two and a half million people reportedly fled the country because of sectarian death squads.
“We didn’t have a problem until al-Maliki came to Syria and urged the government to stop giving visas to Iraqis, to force them back into Iraq,” he said.
“I can’t trust a government that supports the criminals who burned my house when I left.”
The decrease in violence can be partly explained by the fact that the Sunnis were driven out of Shia areas and vice versa, creating places where tensions are less.
There is concern that a sudden influx of refugees will again increase sectarian tensions and bring back the fighting.
Small sarre, good training.
The smallest federated state leads in the field of vocational training, and even shines through the international orientation of its higher schools.
It is only in one area that a deficit weighs on the Sarrois, similar to that of the rest of the country.
"I explained yesterday for the 50th time to a non-Sarrois, that we are not French" - this is the slogan that the smallest federated state, by self-deception, posters for its 50th anniversary.
At this level, France and Luxembourg play a major role in the training system of the Saarland, which is placed fifth in the training monitor of the Cologne Institute of German Economics.
Thus, already traditionally, higher education institutions cooperate closely with neighbouring countries.
The university was founded in Saarbrücken in 1948 by the French.
To date, students have the opportunity to complete their studies with a double or even a triple degree.
This is evidenced by the high rate of 15.6 per cent of foreign students.
The Saar also leads the children of the country to higher education in greater numbers than average - many of them without a high school diploma.
"In Saarland, we take advantage of the vocational training system," says Axel Plünnecke, training expert at IW.
More than one in five young people obtain their degree in a vocational school, so the Saar is more than seven points above the national average.
The possibilities for combining vocational and academic training are also relatively well developed.
Given the number of inhabitants, the dual-degree panel is the second best in Germany.
Despite practical training and increasing demand, however, the number of engineering graduates has fallen by a third in recent years.
That is why the Ministry of Education of Sarroia has forced the higher schools to a marketing campaign in the engineering sciences subjects.
"After the first PISA studies, we celebrated a large number of reforms in general schools," said a spokeswoman for the Ministry of Education.
Thus, the government introduced comparative tests throughout the federated state.
For children to start learning earlier, the last year of kindergarten is out of law - a model that in the meantime other federated states copy as well.
Only future comparative studies will be able to show whether students' performance improves sustainably.
In the PISA studies in 2003, the proportion of students at risk decreased from 29 to 20 percent.
Overall, however, the Saarland has not improved as much as other federated states.
The Bavarians are doing better.
And despite the great sarrois, knowledge of foreign languages is not measured by PISA studies - one could otherwise earn points in this area.
Because the language of the neighbor is mandatory in high schools - even if the Sarrois are not French.
