A fall in wages threatens Germany in 2007.
Despite the strong economy, a real under-value of wages is forecast to threaten German workers this year.
Experts have cited all sorts of reasons to explain their pessimistic prognosis.
According to a calculation by the Hans-Böckler Foundation, employees are expected to see a real decrease in their payroll in 2007 compared to the previous year.
"The fault lies in the low wage development, the increase in the Value Added Tax and the rise in food and energy prices," Gustav Horn of the Institute for Macroeconomics and Economic Research told the Bild newspaper.
There may also be new charges in the area of unemployment insurance for the employee.
Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück told the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" that the planned 3.3 per cent reduction in unemployment insurance for the new year was certainly correct and reasonable in the current situation.
However, the National Employment Agency no longer has the right to be embarrassed to ask the Federation for credits or financial aid, in the words of the SPD politician.
It was reported on Tuesday that the explosion in food and oil prices had pushed the inflation rate to its highest level in 13 years.
