Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like Earth than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind swirls at the poles, similar to those that appear on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning strikes on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" today provided proof of this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus explodes at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud in a cloud, reports Christopher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Natural.
According to the famous theory of cyprin, lightning would have brought life on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: “If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be hardly any living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the infernal twin of Earth, but it remains a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venus research, as no more probes have been on the way to explore this planet since the 1980s.
According to the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several "Nature" articles do not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with Earth from our neighboring planet are more numerous than assumed at first.
Thus, the researchers found, in addition to the already known wind swirls at the North Pole, a swirl of clouds at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called the evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, bears little resemblance to Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it constitutes most of the atmosphere on Venus.
Köhler defends Merkel’s meeting with the Dalai Lama.
The President of the Federal Republic of Germany Köhler calls for an end to the dispute between the parties over the reception of the Dalai Lama to the Chancellery.
He indirectly criticized the SPD for the attacks on the chancellor after the meeting in September.
Federal President Horst Köhler is concerned about the appearance of Germany and summons the grand coalition to close the dispute about the reception of the Dalai Lama.
“We must not present to the outside world a divided nation on this issue,” Köhler told the Handelsblatt.
At the same time, Köhler showed understanding for the reception of the Dalai Lama by Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) in September.
“Human rights have universal validity, even if I have respect for differences between cultures,” Köhler said.
Everyone knows that Germany should maintain a sensitive foreign policy balance, the President of the Federal Republic stressed, but defended Merkel against the accusations that she would organize a new Chinese policy.
The German Chancellor has not distanced herself from the traditional policy of a single China.
“China knows that too,” Köhler said.
Foreign Minister Frank-Walter Steimeier (SPD) had indirectly expressed his dissatisfaction with the reception of the Dalai Lama and had been attacked for this outside the ranks of the CDU.
Steinmeier complained in particular about the CDU's "advantage policy" on foreign policy.
After the reception of the Dalai Lama at the Chancellery, virulent irritations were felt in the German-Chinese relations.
Thus, the Chinese government not only dismissed German Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück (SPD), but according to the Spiegel, also frozen the so-called strategy dialogue of the foreign ministers of the two countries.
Chinese Prime Minister Wen Jiabao is now demanding German Chancellor Angela Merkel recognize that the Dalai Lama’s reception was a mistake.
China refuses to allow European politicians to receive the spiritual leader of Tibet in his official functions, Wen Jiabao said.
The Dalai Lama's words and actions would show that he is trying to separate Tibet from China and other Tibetan regions, which also includes other present-day provinces.
Schäuble warns against riots like those in France.
Street fighting with police, shootings, cars on fire: Wolfgang Schäuble warns against riots like those in France.
Everything must be done so that social dissatisfaction in Germany does not erupt in the streets by violence, the German interior minister demanded.
Burning barricades, gunmen firing on police with hunting rifles: after the serious youth riots in France, German Interior Minister Wolfgang Schäuble (CDU) fears a similar development in Germany.
We need to make sure that a social explosive does not also form in our own country and is disintegrating into violence.
We must take this seriously," he told the "Neue Presse" published in Hanover.
Not all young people would be able to cope with the rapid transformations of social reality.
The Federation, the federated states and the communes were already working hard to reduce the problems, Schäuble said.
This would not only affect the integration of immigrants.
"From integration summits to conferences on Islam, this already shows its first successes."
However, it would be too early for an end to the warning.
Schäuble points out at the same time as in the German suburbs, there are no sociological problems or from the point of view of urbanism as in France.
