In Toulouse too, cars and public buildings burned down.
This is what the President of the Turkish communities in Germany, Kenan Kolat, called for from the German government for greater integration efforts.
Taking into account the riots in France, Kolat warned against the "imitation effects".
The situation in Germany would certainly not be as explosive as in France.
However, there would still be a need to act.
Kolat emphasizes that the unemployment rate among young people under 25 from immigration would be above the average.
First and foremost, more places should be provided for training.
Kolat insisted: "We must give young people a perspective".
The President of the Turkish communities, however, added that social control in families took place more in Germany than in France.
Many young immigrants don’t want to destroy what their parents have built here.
Kolat exhorted, "But we must still be careful."
"Young people should be given the opportunity to participate in work and training."
Meanwhile, in the Parisian suburb of Villiers-le-Bel, everything remained very quiet during the night.
Police units were in place, a helicopter was flying over the area with spotlights.
The authorities in charge reported three arrests as well as a few burned cars and garbage.
Since the conference, a deployment of about 1,000 security forces has ensured calm.
The police will intervene for as long as necessary, Interior Minister Michelle Alliot-Marie announced, after a visit to the suburb.
