Musharraf ruled for the first time in civilian life.
A day after his retirement as army chief, the Pakistani man of power Musharraf was inaugurated as president.
Thus, eight years of domination by the army end.
Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf was sworn in Thursday for a new five-year term.
Pakistani television broadcast the ceremony live at the presidential palace in the capital Islamabad.
Musharraf vowed to respect the Constitution and act for the well-being of the nation.
On Wednesday, he handed over his position as army chief to his confidant Ashfaq Kiyani and thus bowed to international pressure, including that of the United States.
Eight years after his takeover by a bloodless coup, the former general now reigns for the first time as civilian head of state.
By withdrawing from the post of commander-in-chief of the armed forces, Musharraf had fulfilled the main demand of the opposition and the West.
Another central requirement is the end of the state of emergency that Musharraf had decreed on November 3.
Soon after his inauguration, Musharraf will suspend the state of emergency, according to Attorney General Malik Muhammad Qayyum, and thus fulfill another requirement of the West.
The country's Supreme Court, which Musharraf had occupied after the state of emergency with lawyers from his ranks, had rejected all appeals against the controversial re-election of the head of state on October 6.
Meanwhile, five soldiers were killed in the northern tribal region of North Waziristan in an attack on a military convoy, and four others wounded.
According to the army spokesman, a bomb exploded in a street near the border of Afghanistan.
