Von Beust received criticism for the cancellation of the Olympics.
The mayor's regression from Hamburg's bid for the Summer Olympics has met with virulent criticism in politics and the economy.
Many want to keep fighting for the Games on the waterfront.
But Von Beust calls for realism in the appreciation of chances.
The chief executive of the Hamburg Chamber of Commerce, Hans-Jörg Schmidt-Trenz, described an abandonment on Wednesday as "bad for the local economy".
In recent times, no other project had deployed as much motivational force in the city as the idea of the Olympics.
"Without this objective, the political and sporting momentum could not have been maintained in the same measures."
Schmidt-Trenz urges the Senate not to bury the project, but to find a new, longer-term starting point, "which takes another modified agenda as its starting point."
Mayor Ole von Beust stayed on Wednesday to his previous statements, according to which Hamburg's Olympic ambitions were unrealistic until at least 2028.
"It is not Hamburg that decides on a bid for the Olympics, but the German Federation of Olympic Sports," Von Beust told WELT ONLINE.
He refers to the expected decision of the Sports Federation in early December, regarding Munich's candidacy for the 2018 Winter Games.
This preference means for us that, in the time frame we had planned until 2028, we will have no chance.”
However, the dream does not definitely belong to the past, said Von Beust.
The Hamburg Sports Federation (HSB) regretted Beust’s statements.
This would give the impression that Hamburg does not want to run for the Olympic Games in the next 25 years.
"It is too early to close an opportunity, burying the projects already now," HSB President Günter Plöß said on Wednesday.
An abandonment of the candidacy would further contradict the statements of the head of the Senate on the occasion of the reception in the plenary assembly of the German Federation of Higher Schools of Sport.
There, Von Beust would have described Hamburg's bid for the 2015 Universiade as "not a substitute" for the Olympic Games in Hamburg.
The Federation of Higher Schools of Sport had first appointed Hamburg as a candidate city in the past few weeks.
The mayor’s SPD faction has accused the Senate of not using this precious time in the construction of housing in Hamburg.
"The development of the Little Grasbrook has been denied by the Senate for years because it played the Olympic card and excluded the construction of housing," said SPD delegates Carola Veit and Jan Quast.
While the SPD has always called for the Little Grasbrook to have an integrated plan in the Olympics and a later use of housing, the CDU would have relied exclusively on the "Event factor".
The bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics, for its part, would have raised a lot of enthusiasm in Hamburg.
Hamburg, however, had broken up against Leipzig.
They're not Warhol's crates.
The one who connects the concepts Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden are casting shadows on the list of Warhol's works.
A large part of the eighty Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the international authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disappointing result: the other six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the Moderna-Boxes museum is made in 1995 by the Pontus Hul.
The ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curative productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time now speak of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol allowed, with the appellation "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum falsely claimed later that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later cede to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén crates were produced in Malmö in 1990 alone, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, next to the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sculpted, then applied with a brush of paint to white.
The texture of the copies dating back to 1990, on the contrary, reveals that the paint was directly applied without a background layer to the laminated panels, using a roll of paint - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New-York does not come in so much class as a decision, the Moderna Muse will make six
As early as July, the Authentication Board of course announced that it would investigate the “heavy charges” that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
Rebel soldiers in Manila give up
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers abandoned, the same ones who had locked themselves in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the President of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The soldiers in power had just stormed the hotel with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been trapped in the building for hours.
About half of them stood before the courts on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse himself with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who normally had to monitor them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal troops in power closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The Chairperson convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
"People have had enough," said Trillanes.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who commanded the Ranger Scouts' elite unit, said other army units were about to join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a major demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila was already since 2003 the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo.
The insurrection broke down nearly 24 hours after the army refused to join it.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
